<br>
Walking softly to her study, Didi removed a small bag and a package from her desk, and returned to her husband's side.  She smiled at the stern lines of her husband's face, now so many years more careworn than the day they married, but every line familiar and accounted for, the burdens shared and lessened between the two souls bound as one.<br>
<br>
She sat down on the bed beside Tallonar, lips curling in affection at the familiar form beside her.  The silk sheet had slipped down to expose his bare blue chest, and strands of soft white hair brushed his collarbone.  She placed the large, flat package on his dresser for him to open once he awoke; a small bag on her own dresser caught her eye as she passed and made her raise an elegant white eyebrow.  <br>
<br>
Putting down the small bag she held, she paused to investigate the gift left by Tallonar.  Her breath caught at the sight of the pendant inside, glowing with a life of its own.  She unwrapped it carefuly from the mistletoe, smiling in memory, and carefully fastened it around her neck, where it lay warm and almost alive to the touch against her breast.  She could only imagine the cost of such a gift ... but a cost far less than the value she placed on it.<br>
<br>
Picking up her own present to Tallonar she turned back to the bed to find him watching her with sleepy eyes.<br>
<br>
&quot;You like it?&quot; he smiled.<br>
<br>
&quot;You silly, silly man ...&quot; she shook her head with a smile. &quot;of course I do, it's as wonderful as you are, and I shall treasure it, just as I have treasured my husband all these years.&quot;<br>
<br>
Tallonar smiled, relieved, and she moved to join him on the bed, swinging a leg over his to sit astride his knees as he lay on his back.  &quot;Close your eyes.&quot;<br>
<br>
Tallonar obediently did so.  <br>
<br>
Holding the bag in one hand, she removed the rose tied to the bag's drawstring, and ran the petals softly over his face, letting him breathe in the sweet fragrance of the flower.<br>
<br>
&quot;I know that scent...&quot; he murmured, memories flooding back.  &quot;A rose ...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;...of Firiona,&quot; Didi finished.  &quot;Very rare indeed, and risky to obtain.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You carried those roses on our wedding day, I remember,&quot; Tallonar smiled, opening his eyes.  &quot;I was so nervous, I do not recall half of what was said, but I remember that scent filling the small chapel.&quot;<br>
<br>
Didi smiled, slightly surprised he remembered.  &quot;A rose of Firiona, then, to symbolize the love and the vows that unite us, and gives us the strength to fight and the strength to hate.&quot;<br>
<br>
She lay the rose aside and tipped the bag, spilling handfuls of smooth stones across Tallonar's chest.<br>
<br>
&quot;A dozen essences of shadow, one for each month in a year, symbolizing all the years of devotion we've shared.&quot;<br>
<br>
Tallonar chuckled.  &quot;And how many of those years did you spend collecting these for me, as I was learning to smith?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Don't remind me,&quot; Didi replied with a mock shudder.  &quot;But it was worth every minute just to give them to you.&quot;<br>
<br>
Picking a few brightly sparkling stones from amongst the dark ones, she poured them into her husband's hand.  &quot;A dozen blue diamonds, one for each month in a year, to symbolize the years together still to come, and the eternal bond we share.&quot;<br>
<br>
Tallonar blinked at the bright gems mixed with the dark stones, and smiled speechlessly at his wife.  Didi reached into the depths of the bag and drew out one final gem.<br>
<br>
&quot;And, an essence emerald, containing my own life's essence.  Our life's essence, I should say - see how they pulse and flicker as one?&quot;  She held the unset gem beside her necklace, and both watched in fascination as the light of the two gems waxed and waned in exact unison.  &quot;I have not had it set - I thought perhaps you might like to set it yourself in the pommel of your sword.&quot;  She placed the warm stone in Tallonar's hand, and he folded his fingers around it.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://users.bigpond.net.au/stbt/misc/anniversarygift.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
&quot;The rest of your gift is over there, when you are ready to unwrap it.&quot;  Didi carefuly replaced the smooth stones back into the bag, and set it carefully aside with the rose. &quot;But perhaps it can wait a little longer...&quot;  She bent forward and kissed her husband firmly on the lips.<br>
<br>
&quot;Happy anniversary, dear!&quot;<br>
<br>
